## Design decisions (confirmed with user)

- **Fixing the `PromptBuilder#to_messages` arity bug.** Ruby's
  `PromptBuilder#to_messages` calls `@backend.to_messages(@context.messages)`
  (1 arg), but `Ollama`/`OllamaCloud`/`OpenAI` define `to_messages(system, messages)`
  (2 required args) while only `Anthropic`/`Gemini` define `to_messages(messages)`
  (1 arg) — calling `builder.to_messages` directly would raise an
  `ArgumentError` for 3 of the 5 backends in Ruby. This bug never surfaces in
  `example.rb`, which only calls `to_api_payload` (each backend's own
  `to_payload` calls its own `to_messages` internally with the right arity).
  The Python port **fixes this**: every backend's `to_messages` takes a
  uniform `(system, messages)` signature — `Anthropic`/`Gemini` simply ignore
  the `system` argument in their message-list building (they still use
  `context.system` separately inside `to_payload` for the top-level
  `system`/`systemInstruction` field). `PromptBuilder.to_messages()` calls
  `self.backend.to_messages(self.context.system, self.context.messages)`
  uniformly. Document both the fix and the underlying Ruby bug in the
  Python README.
- **`model_info` naming collision.** Ruby's `Backends::Base` defines
  `model_info` twice under one name — a class method `self.model_info(model)`
  (MODELS table lookup) and an instance method `model_info` (no args, cached
  per-instance hash) — legal in Ruby because class methods and instance
  methods are separate namespaces, but Python can't have two same-named
  methods with different signatures on one class. The classmethod is renamed
  to `model_info_for(model)`; the no-arg instance accessor keeps the name
  `model_info` (as a `@property`, matching the more frequently-used name and
  the endless-method-→-property convention from prior steps).

